Functional Interface

Interview Questions

1. What is a functional interface?
-->Answer:
      
      A Functional Interface is an interface that contains exactly one abstract method.
      Introduced in Java 8.
      Used to implement Lambda Expressions and Method References.
      It can have any number of default and static methods.
      
      Example:
      
      @FunctionalInterface
      interface Demo {
          void display();
      }
      


2. What annotation is used to define a functional interface?
-->Answer:

      @FunctionalInterface
      
      Benefits:
      
      Ensures the interface has only one abstract method.
      Gives a compile-time error if another abstract method is added.
      
      Example:
      
      @FunctionalInterface
      interface Test {
          void show();
      }



3. Can a functional interface have multiple abstract methods?
-->
Answer:

No.
It must have exactly one abstract method.
It can have multiple default, static, and private methods (Java 9+).

Invalid Example:

@FunctionalInterface
interface Demo {
    void show();
    void print();   // Compile-time Error
}






4. Name some predefined functional interfaces in the java.util.function package.
-->
| Interface         | Purpose                            |
| ----------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Predicate<T>      | Tests a condition                  |
| Function<T,R>     | Converts one object to another     |
| Consumer<T>       | Consumes data (no return value)    |
| Supplier<T>       | Supplies data (no input)           |
| UnaryOperator<T>  | Same input and output type         |
| BinaryOperator<T> | Operates on two same-type operands |





5. What is the difference between Function, Predicate, and Consumer?
-->
| Interface     | Input | Output    | Method     |
| ------------- | ----- | --------- | ---------- |
| Predicate<T>  | One   | boolean   | `test()`   |
| Function<T,R> | One   | Any Type  | `apply()`  |
| Consumer<T>   | One   | No Return | `accept()` |

Examples:

Predicate

Predicate<Integer> p = n -> n % 2 == 0;

System.out.println(p.test(10));

Output

true

Function

Function<String, String> f = s -> s.toUpperCase();

System.out.println(f.apply("java"));

Output

JAVA

Consumer

Consumer<String> c = s -> System.out.println(s);

c.accept("Hello");





6. Can a functional interface have default or static methods?
-->Answer:

      Yes.
      A Functional Interface can have any number of default and static methods.
      Only one abstract method is allowed.
      
      Example:
      
      @FunctionalInterface
      interface Demo {
      
          void show();
      
          default void display() {
              System.out.println("Default Method");
          }
      
          static void print() {
              System.out.println("Static Method");
          }
      }




7. What happens if you remove @FunctionalInterface annotation?
-->Answer:

The interface still works as a Functional Interface if it has only one abstract method.
The annotation is optional.
Without it, the compiler won't check whether the interface remains functional.





Programs

1. Create a custom functional interface and implement it using a lambda.
-->
@FunctionalInterface
interface Demo {
    void show();
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Demo d = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

        d.show();
    }
}




2. Use a predefined Predicate to check if a number is even.
-->
import java.util.function.Predicate;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Predicate<Integer> even = n -> n % 2 == 0;

        System.out.println(even.test(8));
    }
}
Output

true




3. Use a Function to convert a string to uppercase.
-->
import java.util.function.Function;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Function<String, String> upper = s -> s.toUpperCase();

        System.out.println(upper.apply("java"));
    }
}

Output

JAVA




4. Use a Consumer to print all items in a list.
-->import java.util.*;
import java.util.function.Consumer;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        List<String> list = Arrays.asList("Java", "Python", "SQL");

        Consumer<String> print = s -> System.out.println(s);

        list.forEach(print);
    }
}





5. Use a Supplier to return a random number.
-->import java.util.Random;
import java.util.function.Supplier;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Supplier<Integer> random = () -> new Random().nextInt(100);

        System.out.println(random.get());
    }
}





Interview Tips (Quick Revision)
A Functional Interface has exactly one abstract method.
Annotation: @FunctionalInterface (optional but recommended).
Can have multiple default and static methods.
Used mainly with Lambda Expressions and Method References.
Common predefined functional interfaces:
Predicate → test() → Returns boolean
Function → apply() → Returns transformed value
Consumer → accept() → No return value
Supplier → get() → No input, returns a value
